      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Now I have a comprehensive picture. Let me check a few more critical details and search for the specific event IDs.",
      "timestamp": 1783146471274
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Interesting findings:\n\n1. **RAM**: 2x 8GB DDR4 2400MHz - SK Hynix + Samsung (mixed brands - potential issue)\n2. **RAM Usage**: 71.9% used (11.41/15.88 GB) - high but not critical right now\n3. **Pagefile**: 12GB allocated, 1.73GB used, peak 3.17GB\n4. **CRITICAL FINDING**: Event ID 2004 (Resource-Exhaustion-Detector) - \"System committed memory limit\" events are happening EXTREMELY frequently - dozens per day going back weeks. This is a chronic memory pressure issue.\n5. **Event ID 1796** - appears to be a recurring error, happens almost daily. Let me search what this event is.\n6. **Event ID 1801** - another recurring error, often paired with 1796.\n\nThe fact that there are NO WHEA-Logger events and NO minidump files is significant. This could mean:\n- The BSOD happened but the minidump wasn't written (it gets overwritten or the system couldn't write it)\n- The system crashed so hard it couldn't write the dump\n- The BSOD happened on a different Windows installation if dual-boot\n\nWait - the user said they had the BSOD \"at least a couple times yesterday\". But there's no minidump from yesterday (July 3). Let me check if the BSOD was recent enough to be captured.\n\nActually looking more carefully at the crash dumps folder, I see:\n- explorer.exe.10452.dmp from 20/06/2026\n- explorer.exe.12376.dmp from 22/06/2026\n- Chrome dumps from various dates\n- SoundRec.exe dump from 16/06/2026\n\nNo system minidumps at all in C:\\Windows\\Minidump - the folder is empty. This is unusual for a BSOD. Let me also check for Kernel-Power Event 41 (unexpected shutdown) which would confirm BSODs without minidumps.\n\nLet me also check the BIOS version - HP OMEN 15-ce0xx with BIOS40.28. The latest for this model might be newer.\n\nThe mixed RAM brands (SK Hynix + Samsung) is a notable finding - while they're both DDR4 2400MHz, mixed brands can sometimes cause timing compatibility issues that surface as WHEA errors.\n\nNow let me also search for what Event ID 1796 and 1801 are.",
      "timestamp": 1783146479027
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "websearch",
      "code": "{\"query\": \"Windows Event ID 1796 \\\"Kernel-General\\\" error System meaning\"}",
      "output": "{\n  \"search_id\": \"search_463a0f18b6d344b8ba34a7191efbbfb0\",\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/212584-event-1796-tpm-wmi.html\",\n      \"title\": \" Event 1796 TPM-WMI  - Windows 10 Forums\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"tenforums.com/members/EternalEntity.html)\\n    \\n    Posts : [64](https://www.tenforums.com/search.php?do=finduser&userid=193748&contenttype=vBForum_Post&showposts=1&s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293) Windows 10 Pro x64 22H2 19045.2311 Thread Starter\\n    \\n    **New** 25 Apr 2024 [\\\\#9](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/212584-event-1796-tpm-wmi-post2624400.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293)\\n    \\n    > \\n    > I'll be honest, I stopped worrying about it once checking on here and just figured it was a hinky update causing unimportant errors due to the link RickC posted. My mother board's an Z77Mpower, the BIOS hasn't had a new available update in years but is updated to the latest, Secure Boot is disabled on account of it not even being available on the motherboard. I'd rested easy and found the guid of the error in the log and stopped it logging for now.\\n    > \\n    > In a way I'm glad others have been having it as it wasn't just a mystery problem limited to myself.\\n\\n...\\n\\ncom/general-support/212584-event-1796-tpm-wmi-3.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293 \\\"Show results 21 to 26 of 26\\\") [Next](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/212584-event-1796-tpm-wmi-2.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293 \\\"Next Page - Results 11 to 20 of 26\\\") [Last Last](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/212584-event-1796-tpm-wmi-3.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293 \\\"Last Page - Results 21 to 26 of 26\\\")\\n\\n* Jump to page:\\n\\n  \\nRelated Discussions\\n\\n[Event ID 11 (disk) in Event Viewer - frontal USB ports acting weird](https://www.tenforums.com/drivers-hardware/170928-event-id-11-disk-event-viewer-frontal-usb-ports-acting-weird.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293 \\\"Read more\\\")  \\nin Drivers and Hardware\\n\\nHello, So, I was taking a look at Event Viewer today, and I found lots of events, the source being \\\"disk\\\", with ID 11, about a controller error. As my SSD works fine and everything seems to point to removable drives (since the SSD is 'HardDisk0'...\\n[Intermittent temporary freezes-Event Viewer shows dozens of event 5379](https://www.tenforums.com/performance-maintenance/134010-intermittent-temporary-freezes-event-viewer-shows-dozens-event-5379-a.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293 \\\"Read more\\\")  \\nin Performance & Maintenance\\n\\nI'm having a tough time tracking down an issue with a new system. Occasionally, my system will freeze for a few seconds. The mouse will usually lock in place, but not always. In any case, the system doesn't register input. If audio was playing, the...\\n\\n[Anyone else get Event 2 Kernel-Event Tracing error in Event Viewer?](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/135786-anyone-else-get-event-2-kernel-event-tracing-error-event-viewer.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293 \\\"Read more\\\")  \\nin General Support\\n\\nEvery morning when I switch on my PC I just get one error in Event Viewer..It is Event 2 Kernel-Event Tracing error .\\nUnder General it reads Session \\\"CldfFltLog\\\" failed to start with the following error: 0xC0000022 Ive been seeing this error...\\n\\n[Event Viewer Event ID# 10016 listed four consecutive times at boot??](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/107797-event-viewer-event-id-10016-listed-four-consecutive-times-boot.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293 \\\"Read more\\\")  \\nin General Support\\n\\nHi, I just noticed today that in my Event Viewer I find this item listed four consecutive times after each boot: Log Name: System Source: Microsoft-Windows-DistributedCOM Date: 4/10/2018 3:47:19 PM Event ID: 10016...\\n\\n[Multiple Application Errors (Event 1000) in Event Viewer](https://www.tenforums.com/bsod-crashes-debugging/87734-multiple-application-errors-event-1000-event-viewer.html?s=b8664d409d2de69ef6ab3ac7d5629293 \\\"Read more\\\")  \\nin BSOD Crashes and Debugging\\n\\nHi. I have noticed that during the long duration my PC is on (18 hours), several apps keep getting \"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/212584-event-1796-tpm-wmi-3.html\",\n      \"title\": \"Event 1796 TPM-WMI - Page 3 - Windows 10 Forums\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-05-30\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"s=1d81c97baf7053ad293413c6a5aa0325 \\\"Show results 11 to 20 of 26\\\") 3\\n\\n* Jump to page:\\n\\n1. [](https://www.tenforums.com/members/adzify106.html?s=1d81c97baf7053ad293413c6a5aa0325 \\\"adzify106 is offline\\\")  \\n   [adzify106](https://www.tenforums.com/members/adzify106.html)\\n   \\n   Posts : [5](https://www.tenforums.com/search.php?do=finduser&userid=215217&contenttype=vBForum_Post&showposts=1&s=1d81c97baf7053ad293413c6a5aa0325) Windows 10 Home 22H2 b19045.4412\\n   \\n   **New** 30 May 2024 [\\\\#21](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/212584-event-1796-tpm-wmi-post2631225.html?s=1d81c97baf7053ad293413c6a5aa0325)\\n   \\n   > \\n   > RickC said: [](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/212584-event-1796-tpm-wmi-post2624042.html?s=1d81c97baf7053ad293413c6a5aa0325)\\n   > \\n   > I'm beginning to see a lot of reports emerging about this. From what I read, I'm guessing that Microsoft's algorithm to determine which devices are OK to implement the **Secure Boot** update is possibly faulty.  \\n   >\\n> What's worrying is that there are reports of BSODs and 'failures to boot' as well as the _Event ID 1796 errors_ reported in this thread.  \\n   >   \\n   > One thing that is fairly consistent is agreement that an out-of-date BIOS/UEFI may be a cause. As a result, it appears important, when posting about _Event ID 1796 errors_ , to also include the following information:  \\n   >   \\n   > 1\\\\. Make/model of your device.  \\n   > 2\\\\. BIOS/UEFI date.  \\n   > 3\\\\. Whether your device uses UEFI or Legacy BIOS mode to boot.  \\n   > 4\\\\. If UEFI mode, whether **Secure Boot** is enabled.\\n   > \\n   > \\n   > So I've been tearing my hair out for a few months (probably since this was announced after discovering this retrospectively [Microsoft Updating Windows Secure Boot Keys in 2024 -- Redmondmag.com](https://redmondmag.com/articles/2024/02/13/windows-secure-boot-update.aspx) ) and I've signed up to these forums specifically for this post. I have a Clevo which randomly started having issues booting up.\\nI sometimes get a POST screen, sometimes I get nothing which made me wonder if the GFX or PSU were on the way out, tried HDMI out no signal to monitor. Trouble is many times even though the screen is blank, keyboard RGB backlight works, keyboard and mouse respond and I can hear Windows sounds so the proverbial lights are on but no one is home. Usually it takes a few force power off and back on situations and I can somehow get it back as if nothing was wrong.\\n   > \\n   > I got to the point I backed everything up and then formatted the NVME and put a fresh Win 10 install on yesterday, ran latest updates but the problem persisted. I checked event viewer and it was easy to see because I shut it off at around 9.30PM last night and didn't try turning it on again until 2PM today.. that's when I came across about a $hiteload of critical system errors in event viewer:\\n   > \\n   > Code:\\n   > \\n   > ```\\n\\n...\\n\\n[Anyone else get Event 2 Kernel-Event Tracing error in Event Viewer?](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/135786-anyone-else-get-event-2-kernel-event-tracing-error-event-viewer.html?s=1d81c97baf7053ad293413c6a5aa0325 \\\"Read more\\\")  \\nin General Support\\n\\nEvery morning when I switch on my PC I just get one error in Event Viewer..It is Event 2 Kernel-Event Tracing error . Under General it reads Session \\\"CldfFltLog\\\" failed to start with the following error: 0xC0000022 Ive been seeing this error...\\n\\n[Event Viewer Event ID# 10016 listed four consecutive times at boot??](https://www.tenforums.com/general-support/107797-event-viewer-event-id-10016-listed-four-consecutive-times-boot.html?s=1d81c97baf7053ad293413c6a5aa0325 \\\"Read more\\\")  \\nin General Support\\n\\nHi, I just noticed today that in my Event Viewer I find this item listed four consecutive times after each boot: Log Name: System Source: Microsoft-Windows-DistributedCOM Date: 4/10/2018 3:47:19 P\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.minitool.com/news/event-id-1796.html\",\n      \"title\": \"How to Fix the Event ID 1796 TPM-WMI Error - Full Guide\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-09-28\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"We have other methods to enter BIOS in this post: [How to Enter BIOS Windows 10/8/7 (HP/Asus/Dell/Lenovo, any PC)](https://www.minitool.com/news/how-to-enter-bios-windows-10-8-7-009.html) .\\n\\nStep 2: Go to the **Security** section and find the **Secure Boot** option to disable it. You can follow the on-screen instructions to change the options.\\n\\nOnce you have finished the changes, please save that and exit BIOS.\\n\\nStep 3: Now, you can restart your PC and repeat the same steps as above to enable the **Secure Boot** feature.\\n\\nRelated post: [Secure Boot Is Unsupported or Off in Windows 11/10? [Fixed]](https://www.partitionwizard.com/partitionmagic/secure-boot-is-unsupported.html)\\n\\n### Method 2: Uninstall the Recent Update\\n\\nIf you have downloaded and installed the recent updates, you can try to uninstall them to see if the Event ID 1796 can be fixed.\\n\\nStep 1: Open **Settings** from **Start** and click **Update & Security > Windows Update** .\\n\\n...\\n\\nTo update BIOS, you need to follow these procedures one by one.\\n\\n1. Check the computer’s model name.\\n2. Find the latest BIOS update from the manufacturer’s website.\\n3. Download and unzip the BIOS file.\\n4. Copy the BIOS file to a flash drive.\\n5. Restart the PC to the BIOS screen.\\n6. Back up the current BIOS file.\\n7. Start updating BIOS.\\n\\nFor detailed steps for the above procedures, you can read this post: [How to Update BIOS Windows 10 | How to Check BIOS Version](https://www.minitool.com/data-recovery/how-to-update-bios.html) .\\n\\n## Protect Your Data – MiniTool ShadowMaker\\n\\nSince this error can trigger the BSOD issue or system crashes, you can prevent serious losses by [data backup](https://www.minitool.com/backup-tips/data-backup-and-recovery.html) . MiniTool ShadowMaker is a good choice as [free backup software](https://www.minitool.com/backup/system-backup.html) . It provides a one-click [system backup](https://www.minitool.com/backup-tips/windows-10-backup.\\nhtml) solution and allows quick data recovery. For a better backup experience, more backup sources are available, such as files & folders and partitions & disks.\\n\\nNAS backup is supported. If you want automatic backups, you can configure the backup schemes and schedule settings. For more features, you can download and install the program for a 30-day free trial.\\n\\n[MiniTool ShadowMaker Trial Click to Download 100% Clean & Safe](https://cdn2.minitool.com/?p=sm&e=sm-pro)\\n\\n## Bottom Line\\n\\nHow to fix the Event ID 1796 TPM-WMI error? This post has provided four methods to help fix the system issues. You can follow the solutions and check if this error can be resolved. Hope this article can resolve your concerns.\\n\\n* facebook\\n* twitter\\n* linkedin\\n* reddit\\n\\n## About The Author\\n\\n[Anna](https://www.minitool.com/author/anna34/) [Follow Us](https://x.com/AnnaHe832550)\\n\\nPosition: Columnist\\n\\nAnna is an editor of the MiniTool Team. She worked in this big family since her graduation.\\nHer articles mainly focus on data backup and recovery, disk cloning, and file syncing, committed to resolving the data loss issues users may encounter on their PCs. Besides, more related computer articles are shared here. In her leisure time, she enjoys reading and watching movies. Travel can also be a good choice for her.\\n\\n## User Comments :\\n\\n### Join for Exclusives\\n\\nConnect with us for giveaways, exclusive promotions, and the latest news!\\n\\nPrivacy | Terms & Conditions\\n\\nNorth America, Canada, Unit 170 - 422, Richards Street, Vancouver, British Columbia, V6B 2Z4\\n\\nAsia, Hong Kong, Suite 820,8/F., Ocean Centre, Harbour City, 5 Canton Road, Tsim Sha Tsui, Kowloon\\n\\nCopyright © MiniTool ® Software Limited, All Rights Reserved.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.anavem.com/en/windows-events/windows-event-id-1796-kernel-general-system-time-change\",\n      \"title\": \"Event ID 1796: Windows System Time Change Detection Guide\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-03-17\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Learn about Windows Event ID 1796 from Kernel-General. Understand system time changes, NTP sync issues, and security monitoring for IT professionals.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/Desktops-Archive-Read-Only/event-quot-Kernel-General-1-quot-System-times-changes-every/td-p/5863102\",\n      \"title\": \"\\n\\tevent \\\"Kernel General 1\\\"  System times changes every time - HP Support Community - 5863102\\n\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2016-11-25\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"* HP Community\\n* \\n* Archived Topics\\n* \\n* Desktops (Archived)\\n* \\n* event \\\"Kernel General 1\\\" System times changes every time\\n\\n## event \\\"Kernel General 1\\\" System times changes every time\\n\\nOptions\\n\\n* Mark Topic as New\\n* Mark Topic as Read\\n* \\n* Float this Topic for Current User\\n* Bookmark\\n* Subscribe\\n* Mute\\n* \\n* Printer Friendly Page\\n\\nEntire Community This Category This Board Knowledge base Users cancel\\n\\n[turn on suggested results](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/forums/v4/forumtopicpage.enableautocomplete:enableautocomplete?t:ac=board-id/Audio/thread-id/532382&t:cp=action/contributions/searchactions&ticket=xW1fumQXK_tz_-1)  Auto-suggest helps you quickly narrow down your search results by suggesting possible matches as you type.\\n\\nShowing results for\\n\\nSearch instead for \\n\\nDid you mean: \\n\\nStart a conversation\\n\\nGuidelines\\n\\nJoin the HP Community Solve‑a‑thon | Help Others & Share Your Solutions | Live on Zoom | 2:30 PM to 2:30 AM IST | Every Wednesday [Click here to know more](https://h30434.\\nwww3.hp.com/t5/Community-Blog/HP-Community-Solve-a-thon-Everyone-s-Welcome/ba-p/9621311)\\n\\n## Create an account on the HP Community to personalize your profile and ask a question\\n\\nYour account also allows you to connect with HP support faster, access a personal dashboard to manage all of your devices in one place, view warranty information, case status and more.\\n\\nSign in / Create an account\\n\\n[Learn more](https://support.hp.com/us-en/help/hp-account?jumpid=in_r11498_us/en/topic/ribbon)\\n\\n / Create an account / [Learn more](https://support.hp.com/us-en/help/hp-account?jumpid=in_r11498_us/en/topic/ribbon)\\n\\nArchived This topic has been archived. Information and links in this thread may no longer be available or relevant. If you have a question create a new topic by clicking here and select the appropriate board.\\n\\nbas_altena\\n\\n[bas\\\\_altena](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/2848483)\\n\\n1 0 0 7,819\\n\\nNew member\\n\\n‎11-25-2016 01:21 AM\\n\\nHP Recommended\\n\\n* Mark as New\\n* Bookmark\\n* Subscribe\\n* \\n* Permalink\\n* Print\\n* \\n* Flag Post\\n\\nProduct: 400 G1 i3\\n\\nOperating System: Microsoft Windows 8.1 (64-bit)\\n\\nHi there,\\n\\none of my customers have 6 workstations 400 G1 i3. Problem exists on all of the pc's.  The system time changes every time. CMOS battery allready renewed. BIOS update 2.48 installed. The pc's don't have access to the internet. This pc is Windows 8.1 Pro x64.\\n\\nAny suggestions ?\\n\\nTags (4)\\n\\n* Tags:\\n* 400 G1 i3\\n* Archived\\n* Microsoft Windows 8.1 (64-bit)\\n* source-board-id:Business-PC-Workstation-POS\\n\\nView All (4)\\n\\n1 REPLY 1\\n\\nmax009\\n\\n[max009](https://h30434.www3.hp.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/2842601)\\n\\n128 12 8 7,810\\n\\nApprentice Level 5\\n\\n‎11-25-2016 01:30 AM\\n\\nHP Recommended\\n\\n* Mark as New\\n* Bookmark\\n* Subscribe\\n* \\n* Permalink\\n* Print\\n* \\n* Flag Post\\n\\n**The step by step solution is as follows:**  \\n**1 Boot windows**  \\n**2 click start>>run and type regedit.click OK.**  \\n**3 The windows registry editor should pop up.\\nNavigate with in the explorer to:**  \\n**HKEY\\\\_LOCAL\\\\_MACHINE\\\\\\\\SYSTEM\\\\\\\\CURRENTCONTROLSET\\\\\\\\CONTRO L\\\\\\\\TIME ZONEINFORMATION\\\\\\\\REALTIMEUNIVERSAL needs to have the value of \\\"1\\\"**  \\n**4 click on the TIMEZONE-INFORMATION \\\"folder\\\" from the navigation pane if you haven't already done so.**  \\n**5 This assumes the correct key doesn't exist.If it does,you will just change the existing key value right click on the white space within the folder.Select new>DWORD value.Title the key realtimeisuniversal.Set the value to \\\"1\\\". Hexadecimal should be fine.**  \\n**6 Either reboot and set the clock in macOS or set the clock in windows.you should now able to reboot into either OS and have a correct clock.**\\n\\nArchived This topic has been archived. Information and links in this thread may no longer be available or relevant. If you have a question create a new topic by clicking here and select the appropriat\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.experts-exchange.com/questions/27017552/Disable-event-1-kernel-general-in-windows-2008-R2.html\",\n      \"title\": \"Solved: Disable event 1 kernel-general in windows 2008 R2\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2011-05-04\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Link to home\\n\\n \\n\\nWindows Server 2003\\n\\nWindows Server 2003\\n\\n\\\\--\\n\\nQuestions\\n\\n\\\\--\\n\\nFollowers\\n\\nTop Experts\\n\\nAvatar of jimmy1829\\n\\njimmy1829\\n\\nDisable event 1 kernel-general in windows 2008 R2\\n\\nHi Experts,  \\n  \\nWe desperately need to disable event 1 kernel-general in windows 2008 R2 indicating the system time has changed.  \\n  \\nPlease advise.  \\n  \\nThanks,\\n\\nZero AI Policy\\n\\nWe believe in human intelligence. Our moderation policy strictly prohibits the use of LLM content in our Q&A threads.\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nASKER CERTIFIED SOLUTION\\n\\nAvatar of gheist gheist\\n\\nLink to home\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nmembership\\n\\nLog in or create a free account to see answer.\\n\\nSigning up is free and takes 30 seconds. **No credit card required.**\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nAvatar of jimmy1829 jimmy1829\\n\\nASKER\\n\\nThanks, please see below  \\n  \\nLog Name:      System  \\nSource:        Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-G eneral  \\nDate:          13/01/2011 5:37:33 PM  \\nEvent ID:      1  \\nTask Category: None  \\nLevel:         Information  \\nKeywords:      Time  \\nUser:          SYSTEM\\nComputer:      Database01  \\nDescription:  \\nThe system time has changed to ¿2011¿-¿01¿-¿13T22:37:33.5 00000000Z from ¿2011¿-¿01¿-¿13T22:36:33.3 39397000Z.  \\nEvent Xml:  \\n<Event xmlns=\\\" <http://schemas.microsoft.com/win/2004/08/events/event> \\\">  \\n<System>  \\n<Provider Name=\\\"Microsoft-Windows-Ke rnel-Gener al\\\" Guid=\\\"{A68CA8B7-004F-D7B6- A698-07E2D E0F1F5D}\\\" />  \\n<EventID>1</EventID>  \\n<Version>0</Version>  \\n<Level>4</Level>  \\n<Task>0</Task>  \\n<Opcode>0</Opcode>  \\n<Keywords>0x80000000000000 10</Keywor ds>  \\n<TimeCreated SystemTime=\\\"2011-01-13T22: 37:33.5000 00000Z\\\" />  \\n<EventRecordID>9677</Event RecordID>  \\n<Correlation />  \\n<Execution ProcessID=\\\"4\\\" ThreadID=\\\"80\\\" />  \\n<Channel>System</Channel>  \\n<Computer>YMDB02</Computer >  \\n<Security UserID=\\\"S-1-5-18\\\" />  \\n</System>  \\n<EventData>  \\n<Data Name=\\\"NewTime\\\">2011-01-13T 22:37:33.5 00000000Z< /Data>  \\n<Data Name=\\\"OldTime\\\">2011-01-13T 22:36:33.3 39397000Z< /Data>  \\n</EventData>  \\n</Event>\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nAvatar of gheist gheist\\nNTP client does it every 6 hours.  \\n1 minute offset in 6 hours signifies badly damaged hardware (or that your virtualization solution does not keep time correctly)  \\n  \\nWhat are your time servers? Are your domain controllers in sync?\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nAvatar of jimmy1829 jimmy1829\\n\\nASKER\\n\\nThis behaviour seems really random. Sometimes it happens 3 times a day, sometimes it does not happen in 2 weeks.  \\n  \\nThis is a physical server, and I have seen this event everywhere even on my Windows 7 machine, which syncs with Internet.\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nReward 1 Reward 2 Reward 3 Reward 4 Reward 5 Reward 6\\n\\nEARN REWARDS FOR ASKING, ANSWERING, AND MORE.\\n\\nEarn free swag for participating on the platform.\\n\\n* * *\\n\\nAvatar of gheist gheist\\n\\nit is a normal time synching event. \\\"Windows Time\\\" service is responsible for it.  \\n  \\nparticular message sets time one minute ahead. That is bad. i would recommend to check (with ntpdate from meinberg NTP if no better idea) if all DCs have same time set.\\nThis event is a sign of normal operation otherwise. If you filter then say pay attention to offset of >10min or so.  \\n  \\nYou can use Meinberg NTP to adjust timer speed in place of default NTP. It will report communication error with upstream NTP anyway.\\n\\nWindows Server 2003\\n\\nWindows Server 2003\\n\\n\\\\--\\n\\nQuestions\\n\\n\\\\--\\n\\nFollowers\\n\\nTop Experts\\n\\nWindows Server 2003 was based on Windows XP and was released in four editions: Web, Standard, Enterprise and Datacenter. It also had derivative versions for clusters, storage and Microsoft’s Small Business Server. Important upgrades included integrating Internet Information Services (IIS), improvements to Active Directory (AD) and Group Policy (GP), and the migration to Automated System Recovery (ASR).\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.windowsphoneinfo.com/threads/event-log-kicking-out-kernel-general-event-id-16-on-a-regular-basis-dell-says-its-a.1038919\",\n      \"title\": \"Event log kicking out Kernel-General Event ID 16 on a regular ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2023-08-08\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Event log kicking out Kernel-General Event ID 16 on a regular ...\\nAug 8, 2023 — In one of these Vsphere, we noted that VMs restarted unexpectedly and we got the Event kernel-General with the ID 16 when we access to the MS\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://umatechnology.org/event-id-1796-tpm-wmi-the-secure-boot-update-failed/\",\n      \"title\": \"Event ID 1796, TPM-WMI, The Secure Boot update failed\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-01-10\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Event ID 1796 is logged when there is a failure in the secure boot update process. This event usually originates from the TPM-WMI source and alerts users and system admins about possible security vulnerabilities.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://winevt-kb.readthedocs.io/en/latest/sources/eventlog-providers/Provider-Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General.html\",\n      \"title\": \"Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"<!DOCTYPE html> \\n\\n* [](https://winevt-kb.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html)\\n* [Event Log providers](https://winevt-kb.readthedocs.io/en/latest/sources/eventlog-providers/index.html)\\n* Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General\\n* [ View page source](https://winevt-kb.readthedocs.io/en/latest/%5Fsources/sources/eventlog-providers/Provider-Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General.md.txt)\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General[](#microsoft-windows-kernel-general \\\"Link to this heading\\\")\\n\\nSeen on:\\n\\n* Windows Vista\\n* Windows 2008\\n* Windows 7\\n* Windows 8.0\\n\\n| **Name:**                  | Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General       |\\n| -------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |\\n| **Identifier:**            | {a68ca8b7-004f-d7b6-a698-07e2de0f1f5d} |\\n| **Log type(s):**           | System                                 |\\n| **Log source(s):**         | Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General       |\\n| **Event message file(s):** | %SystemRoot%\\\\\\\\system32\\\\\\\\advapi32.dll   |\\n\\nSeen on:\\n* Windows 2012\\n* Windows 8.1\\n* Windows 10 (1511, 1607, 1703, 1709, 1803, 1809, 1903, 1909, 2004, 20H2)\\n* Windows 2016\\n* Windows 2019\\n* Windows 11 (21H2)\\n\\n| **Name:**                  | Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General                            |\\n| -------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |\\n| **Identifier:**            | {a68ca8b7-004f-d7b6-a698-07e2de0f1f5d}                      |\\n| **Log type(s):**           | System                                                      |\\n| **Log source(s):**         | Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-General                            |\\n| **Event message file(s):** | %SystemRoot%\\\\\\\\system32\\\\\\\\Microsoft-Windows-System-Events.dll |\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://forums.malwarebytes.com/topic/173863-event-id-5-kernel-general-error-in-event-viewer\",\n      \"title\": \"Event ID 5 Kernel-General error in Event Viewer - Malwarebytes for Windows Support Forum - Malwarebytes Forums\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2015-10-15\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"+ [Share on Pinterest](https://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=https://forums.malwarebytes.com/topic/173863-event-id-5-kernel-general-error-in-event-viewer/&media=)\\n  \\n  More sharing options...\\n* \\n\\n[Coroner](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/193872-coroner/ \\\"Go to Coroner's profile\\\")\\n\\n[Coroner](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/193872-coroner/ \\\"Go to Coroner's profile\\\")\\n\\nOctober 10, 2015 10 yr in [Malwarebytes for Windows Support Forum](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/forum/41-malwarebytes-for-windows-support-forum/)\\n\\n*\\n\\n## Featured Replies\\n\\nPrevious carousel slide Next carousel slide\\n\\n[Coroner](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/193872-coroner/ \\\"Go to Coroner's profile\\\")\\n\\n### [Coroner](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/193872-coroner/ \\\"Go to Coroner's profile\\\")\\n\\nMembers\\n\\n* [9 posts](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/193872-coroner/content/ \\\"Posts\\\")\\n* 0 Reputation\\n\\n[Coroner](https://forums.malwarebytes.\\ncom/profile/193872-coroner/ \\\"Go to Coroner's profile\\\")\\n\\n### [Coroner](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/193872-coroner/ \\\"Go to Coroner's profile\\\") Members\\n\\nOctober 10, 2015 10 yr\\n\\nAuthor stats\\n\\nOctober 10, 2015 10 yr\\n\\nWelcome,  \\nI have a problem. Every day I have this error in event viewer, system log:\\n\\n{Registry Hive Recovered} Registry hive (file): \\\\\\\\??\\\\\\\\C:\\\\\\\\ProgramData\\\\\\\\Malwarebytes\\\\\\\\Malwarebytes Anti-Malware\\\\\\\\S-1-5-21-4089430802-3287748835-2730757419-1001-0-ntuser.dat was corrupted and it has been recovered. Some data might have been lost.\\n\\nThis error repeats every day at about 3:00AM.\\n\\nI did system integrity check and hard drive check (CHKDSK) - no errors.\\n\\nMaybe someone could help me? Thanks in advance.\\n\\n[daledoc1](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/29793-daledoc1/ \\\"Go to daledoc1's profile\\\")\\n\\n### [daledoc1](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/29793-daledoc1/ \\\"Go to daledoc1's profile\\\")\\n\\nHonorary Members\\n\\n* [22\\\\.8k posts](https://forums.malwarebytes.\\ncom/profile/29793-daledoc1/content/ \\\"Posts\\\")\\n* 0 Reputation\\n\\n[daledoc1](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/29793-daledoc1/ \\\"Go to daledoc1's profile\\\")\\n\\n### [daledoc1](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/profile/29793-daledoc1/ \\\"Go to daledoc1's profile\\\") Honorary Members\\n\\nOctober 10, 2015 10 yr\\n\\nAuthor stats\\n\\nOctober 10, 2015 10 yr\\n\\nHello and :welcome: , @Coroner:  \\n  \\nI saw your thread over at tenforums.com here: [Event ID 5 Kernel-General error in Event Viewer](http://www.tenforums.com/antivirus-firewalls-system-security/25863-event-id-5-kernel-general-error-event-viewer.html)  \\n  \\nThanks for coming over here.  \\n  \\nNormally, the first step would be to suggest a clean MBAM reinstall, especially since you upgraded to Win10 with MBAM installed.\\n\\nHowever, given the nature of the Error Code 5 events which **appear to be** related to your scheduled Threat scans, I thought that the QA team might want to collect some basic logs first.\\n\\n...\\n\\ncom/forum/41-malwarebytes-for-windows-support-forum/ \\\"Go to Malwarebytes for Windows Support Forum\\\")\\n\\n[IPS spam](https://cleantalk.org/ips-cs-4-anti-spam-plugin) blocked by CleanTalk.\\n\\n### Recently Browsing 0\\n\\n* No registered users viewing this page.\\n\\n1. [Home](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/ \\\"Home\\\")\\n2. [Malwarebytes for Home Support](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/forum/40-malwarebytes-for-home-support/)\\n3. [Malwarebytes for Windows Support Forum](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/forum/41-malwarebytes-for-windows-support-forum/)\\n4. Event ID 5 Kernel-General error in Event Viewer\\n\\n* [All Activity](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/discover/)\\n\\n* [She's a threat to inboxes everywhere](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/index.php?app=core&module=system&controller=redirect&do=advertisement&ad=5&key=17e0a94ea6b7855ef7ac7df210a4b8183b30e2107f4530410c49f44f64581714)\\n* [She's a threat to inboxes everywhere](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/index.php?\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"warnings\": null,\n  \"usage\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"sku_search\",\n      \"count\": 1\n    }\n  ],\n  \"session_id\": \"ses_0d4353da7ffeYcDQulSCL0yoGQ\"\n}",
