      "text": "Now I have all the data needed. Here is the comprehensive **Enterprise Root Cause Analysis**:\n\n---\n\n## WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR (0x00000124) - Root Cause Analysis\n\n### System Profile\n| Component | Details |\n|---|---|\n| **Machine** | HP OMEN 15-ce0xx (\"AndieKobbie-OMEN\") |\n| **OS** | Windows 10 Pro 19045 (22H2) |\n| **CPU** | Intel 7th Gen (Kaby Lake, likely i7-7700HQ) |\n| **GPU** | Intel HD 630 + NVIDIA GTX 1050 |\n| **RAM** | 2x8GB DDR4-2400 **(mixed: SK Hynix + Samsung)** |\n| **Storage** | ADATA SX6000NP 512GB NVMe + HGST 1TB HDD |\n| **BIOS** | AMI F.28 (version 40.28) |\n\n---\n\n### Evidence Found\n\n**1. Kernel-Power Event 41 (Unexpected Shutdown) - 8 occurrences:**\n| Date | Time |\n|---|---|\n| **2026-07-03** | **16:15 UTC** |\n| **2026-07-03** | **10:09 UTC** |\n| 2026-06-20 | 09:41 & 05:09 |\n| 2026-06-17 | 19:40 |\n| 2026-05-15 | 02:39 |\n| 2026-05-12 | 11:57 |\n| 2026-05-07 | 13:51 |\n\nThis confirms your BSOD. **Two crashes yesterday alone**, matching your report.\n\n**2. Chronic Memory Pressure (Event 2004) - 60+ occurrences** going back to June 23. Chrome eating 3-3.5GB, Hyper-V vmmem 1.1GB, opencode.exe 800MB+. Your 16GB is at **71.9% utilization** routinely exhausting the commit limit.\n\n**3. TPM-WMI Event 1796 - Secure Boot update failures** (error 0x800700c1) happening **daily** since at least June 23. Your BIOS F.28 is too old for Microsoft's latest Secure Boot key updates.\n\n**4. Mixed RAM modules** - SK Hynix + Samsung in a laptop. Different vendors = potentially different timings/subtimings.\n\n**5. NO minidumps written** - C:\\Windows\\Minidump is empty. The crash is so severe Windows can't write the dump file, which typically indicates either CPU-level failure or memory controller failure during the crash.\n\n---\n\n### Root Cause Probability Assessment\n\n| Rank | Cause | Probability | Evidence |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **1** | **Memory pressure + mixed RAM instability** | **55%** | 60+ resource exhaustion events, mixed-brand RAM, no minidumps (memory controller overwhelmed) |\n| **2** | **CPU/VREG degradation on aging laptop** | **25%** | 8 unexpected shutdowns over months, no minidumps (CPU-level crash), HP OMEN 15-ce0xx is ~7-8 years old hardware |\n| **3** | **Outdated BIOS causing Secure Boot/firmware conflict** | **15%** | Daily Event 1796 failures, known Microsoft Secure Boot key update issue |\n| **4** | **NVMe SSD controller errors** | **5%** | ADATA SX6000NP is budget NVMe, but no SMART warnings found |\n\n---\n\n### Fixability Score (iFix-style Scale)\n\n| Score | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **5/10 - Moderate** | |\n\n**Breakdown:**\n- **BIOS update**: Easy fix (download from HP, flash). But note: HP had a major BIOS update issue in April 2026 bricking machines with BitLocker loops. Proceed with caution. (+2 points)\n- **Memory pressure management**: Easy to reduce Chrome/Hyper-V usage, or set pagefile manually. (+1 point)\n- **Mixed RAM**: Would need to buy a matched kit (~$30-40 for 2x8GB DDR4-2400). (+1 point, but requires purchase)\n- **CPU degradation**: **Not fixable** without hardware replacement. (-1 point)\n- **Secure Boot TPM issue**: Needs BIOS update + Secure Boot toggle. Risky on HP due to recent bricking reports. (+0 points)\n\n---\n\n### Reliability Assessment\n\n| Metric | Rating |\n|---|---|\n| **Current stability** | **Low** - 2 crashes yesterday, 8 in 2 months |\n| **Risk of recurrence** | **HIGH** - Chronic memory pressure is ongoing |\n| **Data loss risk** | **MODERATE** - SSD appears OK but crashes during write operations are dangerous |\n| **Progression risk** | **MODERATE-HIGH** - If CPU/VREG is degrading, crashes will increase in frequency |\n\n---\n\n### Can You Safely Improve Temperature?\n\n**Yes, you can monitor and improve temperatures without stress testing.** Here is what I recommend as a safe, non-stress approach:\n\n1. **Monitor temps passively** - Install HWMonitor (free, read-only, no stress). Just watch idle and during normal use. This laptop (i7-7700HQ + GTX 1050) should idle around 40-55C CPU, and under normal browsing 60-75C. If you see **90C+** during normal use, thermal throttling could be contributing to WHEA errors.\n\n2. **Clean the vents** - On the HP OMEN 15-ce0xx, the intake vents are on the bottom and exhaust on the back. Use compressed air to blow dust out. This alone can drop temps 5-15C.\n\n3. **Elevate the rear** - A laptop stand or even a book under the back edge improves airflow significantly.\n\n4. **Components are OK for monitoring** - The fact that both GPUs show \"OK\" status and both drives show \"OK\" status is encouraging. No SMART errors found.\n\n---\n\n### Recommended Fix Priority (No Stress Testing Required)\n\n1. **Immediate**: Reduce memory pressure - close unnecessary Chrome tabs, consider disabling Hyper-V if not actively using VMs (vmmem is eating 1.1GB). This is the most likely trigger.\n2. **Low risk**: Update BIOS to latest from HP support site (but research the specific version for your exact model first - avoid the April 2026 problematic updates).\n3. **Moderate**: Purchase a matched 2x8GB DDR4-2400 kit (~$30) to replace the mixed SK Hynix/Samsung modules.\n4. **Optional**: Clean dust from cooling system + elevate laptop.\n5. **Monitor**: Install HWMonitor and watch temps passively during normal use for a week.\n\nThe memory pressure issue is the most actionable and most likely contributing factor. It costs nothing to address.",
