      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Now I have a very comprehensive picture. Let me summarize the key findings:\n\n## System Profile\n- **Computer**: HP OMEN by HP Laptop 15-ce0xx (AndieKobbie-OMEN)\n- **OS**: Windows 10 Pro 19045 (22H2)\n- **CPU**: Intel 7th gen (Kaby Lake) - i7-7700HQ likely for this model\n- **GPU**: Intel HD 630 + NVIDIA GTX 1050\n- **RAM**: 2x 8GB DDR4 2400MHz - **MIXED BRANDS** (SK Hynix + Samsung)\n- **Storage**: ADATA SX6000NP 512GB NVMe SSD + HGST 1TB HDD\n- **BIOS**: AMI BIOS version 40.28 (likely F.28)\n- **Motherboard**: HP 838F\n\n## Critical Findings\n\n### 1. Kernel-Power Event 41 (Unexpected Shutdown) - **8 occurrences**\n- 2026-07-03T16:15 (yesterday!)\n- 2026-07-03T10:09 (yesterday!)\n- 2026-06-20 (2 occurrences)\n- 2026-06-17\n- 2026-05-15\n- 2026-05-12\n- 2026-05-07\n\nThis confirms the BSODs! Event 41 is the \"kernel power\" event that Windows logs when it shuts down unexpectedly (like a BSOD). The user said they had it \"at least a couple times yesterday\" - and we see TWO Event 41 entries on July 3rd (yesterday).\n\n### 2. NO Minidumps, NO WHEA-Logger events\n- C:\\Windows\\Minidump is empty\n- No WHEA-Logger events in the system log\n- This is significant: either the BSODs happened so fast Windows couldn't write dumps, or the system crashed too hard to write them\n\n### 3. Chronic Memory Pressure - **Event ID 2004 (Resource-Exhaustion-Detector)**\n- DOZENS of occurrences, going back weeks (June 24 through July 4)\n- \"System committed memory limit\" exhausted\n- Chrome consuming 3-3.5GB, vmmem (Hyper-V) using 1.1GB, opencode.exe using 800MB+\n- Current state: 71.9% RAM used (11.41/15.88 GB)\n- 12GB pagefile allocated### 4. TPM-WMI Event ID 1796 - **Secure Boot update failures**\n- \"The secure boot update failed to update a secure boot variable. Error Unknown HResult Error code: 0x800700c1\"\n- Happening almost daily since at least June 23\n- This is a known Microsoft/HP issue related to Secure Boot key updates\n- HP BIOS version 40.28 may be too old for the latest Secure Boot variable updates\n\n### 5. Mixed RAM Brands\n- Slot 1: SK Hynix HMA81GS6AFR8N-UH (8GB DDR4 2400)\n- Slot 2: Samsung M471A1K43CB1-CRC (8GB DDR4 2400)\n- While both DDR4 2400, different manufacturers can have different timings/voltages\n\n### 6. Hyper-V Enabled (vmmem process)\n- vmmem process using 1.1GB+ RAM\n- Multiple Hyper-V virtual ethernet adapters\n- VMware also installed (virtual ethernet adapter present)\n- VMX was not present/not enabled in BIOS at some point (Feb 2026)\n\nNow let me compile the full analysis.",
